Keeping the peace <br>
<br>
John Lloyd <br>
<br>
<br>
JOHN Challens and Eddie Howse clambered down into the waiting boat, and as it pulled away took a last look back at HMS Plym. The frigate, moored in a lagoon at the centre of the Monte Bello Islands, off the north-west coast of Australia, bobbed gently in the water, its lights blazing and generators humming. It was an unremarkable and outdated example of the Royal Navy fleet. But Plym was about to become highly remarkable; deep in its belly sat Britain's first atomic bomb. <br>
<br>
A short time later Challens and Howse, scientists working on the atomic programme, arrived back at the control centre on the islands, known as H1, seven miles from where Plym was securely anchored. Challens handed over the master key, which was inserted into the firing panel. History was minutes away. <br>
<br>
William Penney was watching from the bridge of HMS Campania, an aircraft carrier that had delivered around 100 British scientists to the islands three months before. As the director of the British atomic bomb project, Penney's reputation and pride were invested in the success of the experiment. The nervous physicist, who normally wore glasses, had been told to remove them to avoid being blinded by a reflection of the flash. <br>
<br>
Penney need not have worried. On October 3, 1952, at 36 seconds before 1am UK time, 29 minutes and 24 seconds past nine Monte Bello time, Britain joined the nuclear club. When the bomb was detonated, HMS Plym was instantly vaporised; it took one-hundredth of a second for a fireball to leap 350ft high and spread 500ft wide, and at half a second it stretched across a third of a mile; the terrible mushroom shape gradually emerged, reaching 1,800ft high. &quot;...all round, a blinding light bathed the ships and the ocean from horizon to horizon,&quot; one observer was to write afterwards. Another, who had been standing with his back to the explosion on the Campania, wrote: &quot;The sight that met our eyes as we turned was vastly more terrifying than can be appreciated from any photograph. The great, grey-black mass, just flowering at the top like a tremendous cauliflower, appeared, even at a distance, to be towering right over us.&quot; <br>
<br>
It had been a struggle getting to this point. The bomb was based on the &quot;Fat Boy&quot; dropped by the Americans on Nagasaki, a plutonium &quot;implosion&quot; bomb. But Britain's wartime allies were keen to maintain their atomic hegemony and had refused to help. Because of this the bomb in Plym's bowels had not been a guaranteed success. <br>
<br>
That the experiment worked was enormously important for Britain. America had been first to develop the bomb, the Soviet Union second, and, as the third, the UK ensured its continuing place at the top table, both militarily and in terms of international influence. Britain now had leverage in the nuclear stand-off between east and west that was to dictate international politics for the better part of the rest of the 20th century, taking the planet to the brink of destruction. <br>
<br>
This week, 50 years on from the Monte Bello test, to propose nuclear power - in both its civilian and military varieties - as a means for bringing the world closer together, would seem to be a demented venture. <br>
<br>
Let us run through the arguments against such a proposition. How can we make this claim with such recently averted nuclear catastrophes as Three Mile Island, and one of considerable (if less than it might have been) scope in Chernobyl? With the problem of nuclear waste still tormenting the governments of the nuclear-powered states? With a new nuclear standoff between the two sub-continental powers of India and Pakistan? With weapons-grade uranium and plutonium sloshing about in the black markets of the world? With Saddam Hussein letting it be known to the three African states with nuclear programmes that he would pay top dollar for some of that material? With all that, how to propose that the coming of nuclear fission into the world has been anything other than a disaster which we must, somehow, learn to suppress? <br>
<br>
But, 50 years after Britain set off down the route of a civilian and military nuclear programme, we should think out of the box of horrors which has been erected around the atom. Most things, and events, have a double life: their own intrinsic properties, and what you make of them. <br>
<br>
There are intrinsic properties to atomic physics which make it a horror - but then there are to biology, and to chemistry, the two other branches of science which have helped put Saddam onto the world stage as our first fear. There are - we have recently discovered - intrinsic properties to the humble nail file, for that matter, which is why since last September they are routinely confiscated at the gates to departure areas in airports. <br>
<br>
But the intrinsic properties of nuclear fission are so awesome and have been so etched on our contemporary media-fed consciousness by endless clips of Nagasaki, Hiroshima and the results, that they have come to be in another league. That means it is time to think out of the box. Time to think how nuclear power could, as well as blowing us apart, bring us together. <br>
<br>
Nuclear power, in a different age, was seen as benign. Lots of people now want to ban it from the world: in the decade or two after the power stations began to appear in Britain, people wanted it in their village. The physicist Professor Ian Fells recalls that &quot;in the heady days of the 1960s, the residents of Seaton Carew in County Durham demanded to know why they were to have a new coal-fired power station built close to their small town. Why, they asked, can't we have one of these clean nuclear stations?  No sooner asked than delivered: a gas-cooled reactor station was built, and hums there still. <br>
<br>
That was then: but now, after campaigns, and political advances, by European Greens (who shared power in France until last year, and still do in Germany after increasing their vote) nuclear power has become a kind of taboo. <br>
<br>
&quot;In Western Europe,&quot; says John Rich, Director General of the World Nuclear Association, &quot;the anti-nuclear movement has become entrenched and quasi-religious. Environmentalists have responded by nurturing a romantic passion for renewables that has only intensified their animosity to nuclear power.&quot; <br>
<br>
But we are entering into a new era. The latter part of that half-century since we started getting nuclear-made electricity through the wires has been a defensive one for the nuclear industry. Right now, a new offensive is starting. Earlier this year, Tony Blair's own think tank, the Strategy Unit, put out an Energy Review. It showed that we are successful at producing power: so much so that we are one of only two of the big advanced industrial states which exports energy to others. It also shows that this is going to stop soon: our demand for energy, on any normal projection, is going up (by around 25% to 2020), and we will soon have to become an importer. <br>
<br>
Coal and gas, our most popular way of getting electricity, send a lot of carbon into the air. If gas stations replaced all the nuclear ones which are retiring over the next decade, carbon emissions would rise by 20% and we would be nowhere in the virtuous league of carbon-decreasing countries. We are trying - not as hard as some countries, like Canada - to develop renewable energy sources, and the proportion is slowly growing. But it's expensive, disruptive, mainly based in Scotland and wont on the most optimistic forecasts provide more than 10% of the supply by the end of the first quarter of this century. <br>
<br>
We need more nuclear - ironically, to keep us clean. Nuclear stations produce almost no carbon emissions. They do, of course, produce nuclear waste: and we have had scares on nuclear waste, scary enough to make us doubt the wisdom of adding to the dumps, and mindful of the fact that no comprehensive solution to waste has yet been found. <br>
<br>
However, that too may be ending. Part of the reason the US nuclear industry is talking of a renaissance in nuclear power (apart from having a government friendly to every source of energy except renewables) is that the geological repository for nuclear waste at Yucca Mountain is likely to get presidential approval soon; at the same time, Sweden, Finland and Russia are all preparing long-term storage facilities. These cannot be risk-free: but the countries concerned, with very different governments, have concluded the risk of energy gaps is larger. <br>
<br>
Nuclear power is a global industry: indeed, Third World countries are now introducing plants much more aggressively than the rich states. Waste disposal is also global; so is nuclear inspection and monitoring. Finally - Chernobyl again - nuclear disasters are usually global in potential scope. <br>
<br>
We have to build on the global nature of the industry. The International Atomic Energy Authority has some of the most intrusive powers of any agency; it has them because of the perceived dangers. In this is a glimpse of co-operation, based on self-interest, which could make of civilian nuclear power an instrument as close to secure as such an intrinsically explosive technology can offer. The force which drives the demand for more energy - world development, the desire to stay rich and to get richer - will not abate. Better to recognise, tame and internationalise it. <br>
<br>
Fear was the spur for the development of nuclear technologies. Fear that German scientists would be first with an atomic bomb, as they had been first with rocket technology which might, had it been developed earlier, have turned the war in Germany's favour. The British and US scientists who developed the bomb that was used on two Japanese cities had fears of their own about its use, but were more fearful of the technology being used by the enemy. Fear brought us nuclear weapons, whose technology then gave us nuclear power. <br>
<br>
Fear will keep nuclear weapons. There is no realistic prospect of an end to nuclear proliferation soon. The availability of weapons-grade material after the collapse of the Soviet Union, and the malign example set by India and Pakistan, means that nuclear weapons programmes are now more rather than less likely for medium-sized states. The nuclear club which existed for three decades after the war is no longer exclusive, nor can it be. <br>
<br>
We are entering into an unstable and dangerous period: as the US writer Norman Mailer recently remarked, we are more conscious than ever that we will be lucky to get out of this century in as good shape as we got into it. The dossier presented to people and parliament last week by the Prime Minister foresaw Saddam acquiring a nuclear capacity within a year or two: he has the rockets, the scientist and lacks only the uranium. He could wreak havoc on Israel, which would respond in kind; he could threaten his neighbours (such as Kuwait) into submission; he could reach British bases in Cyprus. <br>
<br>
If Saddam has been nationalÅEover the past decade in attempting no external military adventure (as opposed to continued domestic suppression), will he remain national in war, with nothing to lose? We do not know the answer; nor do we know the answer to the question of the ultimate nationality of the nuclear stand-off in the Indian sub-continent. The West had several escalations during the Cold War with the Soviet Union which might have triggered responses which plunged into Armageddons: why should the same not be true of two states mired in bitter hostility, unused to the protocols of prolonged, nerve-grinding power plays which never come to strikes? We have done scenarios of nuclear exchanges, all of which saw tens of millions dead and injured. The twin outcomes of massive and instant human disaster and potential for spreading conflict would be unmanageable. <br>
<br>
There is no quietist option. The reason why we confront invasion of Iraq is that the best guess from the intelligence reports points to Saddam becoming more of a threat in a year than now. The reason why we have to continue to urge the diplomatic option on India and Pakistan is that left to themselves, they are more likely to go to war than not. However much we have created these hideous situations - indeed, the more responsible we have been for them - the larger the duty which now lies on the advanced and wealthy states to manage them back to a kind of stability. <br>
<br>
Stability is not impossible - even if it is likely to be a nervous affair, always at the mercy of the unexpected, or the sudden appearance of an ambitious tyrant. The good story, almost forgotten, is the continued, jolting decline of the two largest armories, those of the US and Russia. Russian weakness is a large part of the reason for this: but with Russian weakness has also come Russian realism, and the possibility of a country willing to accept its reduced destiny as that part of Europe which marches from its centre to its Eurasian tip. <br>
<br>
Condoleezza Rice, the US National Security Advisor, is fond of saying that the attachment of Russia to the West, and the end of the great division in Europe, is one of the largest prizes which we may gain from these early years of the 21st century. The other is the peaceful enfolding of another subaltern nuclear power, China, into a world competing only in trade and sports. That will be a slower process: whoever picks up the mantle of Chinese leadership, he will not be a democrat, nor one reconciled to US domination. Contest and alarms are inescapable. <br>
<br>
But there is more that can unite than divide. Both Chinese and Russian leaderships desperately need economic growth to continue. Their populations will fragment, or become desperate, without it. Both need peace more than war; even in the pursuit of aims said to concern the national honour, such as the re-taking of Taiwan, they are unlikely to go beyond carefully calibrated threats. <br>
<br>
At a recent retreat for ambassadors to the UN, both the Chinese and Russian envoys, permanent members of the Security Council, began to admit what their countries have never admitted in public: that the world had to be managed, and sometimes that would take military strength. That in countries which had become dysfunctional - failed states - and those which had become menaces, a last resort military intervention may be the only way to stabilise the situation. <br>
<br>
The shift in attitudes presaged in these off-the-record discussions is momentous. It implies that states whose public posture has been - and may be again - that the US is indulging in adventurism, admit that there is a role for global policemen. <br>
<br>
The next stage is to make them share the policeman's beat. Other states can compete with US hyperpower on its own terms. If the US aim really is to make and keep the world a safer place, and if the major powers will share that aim for their own purposes, there is no longer an overriding ideological or geo-strategic reason why they should not co-operate with each other to do so. <br>
<br>
The intrinsic property of our divided, nuclear world is risk - at times, grave, hideous risk. What we can make of that is managed risk: a coming together in agreement to carry on living, to get out of this century alive and well, and to leave a planet which is sustainable. Nuclear power, still among the most extraordinary advances we have made, at least concentrates our mind on our own extinction. And, we should hope, how to avoid it.<br>
